text.text: A Guide to Camberwell

For years a popular corner of the city among London’s young and artistic (on account of the prestigious Camberwell Art College and proximity to Goldsmiths), it’s only in the last few years or so that Camberwell has started becoming a destination for everyone else. Still rough around the edges but with plenty of gems to excavate, we took our explorer’s kits, safari hats and all, to see what’s a poppin’. Camberwell. Large. Let’s go.
Best for… pancake vibes

tip.text:
Cameroonian Evangel has been bringing his friendly and colourful vibes to the good people of Camberwell for a while now, so don't be surprised to find local creatives hanging out and working here all day long.

The coffee might not be anything special but the crepes are going down in a big way - sweet or savoury. Have a go on the gluten and dairy free galettes filled with organic, seasonal vegetables, while maybe a strawberry and chocolate crepe would be a fitting dessert. Heck, even if crepes aren't your thing you'll love this spot.

text.text: Despite everyone trying so hard to be bohemian these days it’s fairly rare to stumble across the real thing. Maloko’s vibe is effortlessly cool, from the funky world music playlists to the colourful, hippy-dippy furniture and interior design: the African influence is an inescapable and wonderful thing. The best thing about this cute vegetarian crêperie might well be Evangel, the Cameroonian owner and chef: he speaks multiple tongues, dresses like a rasta and is just one of the warmest characters round these parts.
Best for… diggin’ in them crates

tip.text:
Whether you're looking to shift your old records onto more appreciative hands or looking to find yourself an LP or two then this is the spot in Camberwell. These guys might not specialise in a particular genre but don't let that trick you into thinking they don't know what they're doing - when new stock drops every Saturday you'll catch plenty regulars queueing up outside.

Fun trivia: collector Tom once came across an old, unreleased Mick Jagger and John Lennon collaboration. It was then bought by a 'mystery bidder' at an auction; a few years later it appeared on a Best of Jagger compilation. No prizes for guessing the bidder.

text.text: The go-to spot for all collectors of Camberwell, expect to find a long queue at the doors of Rat Records on Saturdays when the new stock drops. These guys are well aware of the menace that is the internet and make sure their prices are competitive with those found online to make sure people continue to flick through (and buy) records under their roof. There’s no specialist genre, just good music. All CDs are 3 quid (yeah, some people still cop CDs).
Best for… your art & coffee fix

tip.text:
Gallery cafes always seem to be good for inner peace, dontcha think, and The Habit (in Camberwell’s South London Gallery) ain’t no different. A mellow modern bistro, it’s ideal for a spot of midweek working or a couple of bloody Marys to lessen the pain after a Bussey Building blowout. On a sunny day you'll be wanting a spot in the walled garden with milkshake in hand and an eggy brunch firmly on its way.

This is the second cafe from the good folks who brought us The Habit in Nunhead back in 2015, and whether you’re after avo on toast or a flat white - their banging coffee is from Old Spike roastery in Peckham - these guys know what’s up. Kudos to The Habit for keeping things simple and South London fabulous.

Best for... a 2am takeaway

tip.text:
What’s the best thing you can do with £8? If you’ve answered, ‘go to FM Mangal on Camberwell Church Street and get the lamb shish box meal’, then you’ve got it right. FM Mangal is, for our money, the best kebabby to be found in South: a typical no-frills Turkish joint where the sweet elixir of smoking coals charring meat to perfection wafts out the door and brings in any local with an interest in good food.

The tender meat here comes with dope company: fragrant rice, fresh salad, charred flat breads, pomegranate molasses and complimentary charcoal-grilled onions in a sweet and sour vinegary sauce. Served up by a lovely staff, you’re not getting tablecloths or airs and graces; you're getting an ideal bite when you can't be arsed to cook or a venue for a lively group dine out.

Best for… an ethical cup of joe

tip.text:
Seasonal, ethical coffee blends and simple but tasty breakfasts: while this might not be rocket science, it can be difficult to get the basics right at times. The good folk over at Daily Goods were tired of trekking Eastward to find spaces to hang in with like-minded people, so they brought what they were after to Camberwell themselves. DIY motherfuckers.

Tuck into the grilled cheese (the owner's American and swears we don't know a thing about cheese toasties) or homemade muesli and smash out a spot of remote working. Sounds alright doesn't it?

text.text: A place for skaters and creatives by skaters and creatives: sometimes you’ve just gotta make it happen if it’s not popping off already. This is that hangout spot every neighbourhood needs: good coffee, simple brunch options, laid back vibe. These guys care about the ethics of coffee, making sure they work with roasters who give as much back to farmers as possible - the seasonal beans come from Workshop and you can bet the blend is lovely.
Best for… mega cheap eats

tip.text:
If you're after mega cheap, mega delicious Lebanese munch then this is a killer spot. The menu is as simple as it is satisfying - the name of the venue pretty much tells the story. Wraps and mezze are what you're looking at here and nothing will set you back more than a fiver.

A falafel wrap is £3.50, while a shawarma comes for £4.50 - they are absolutely banging and very filling; the steady stream of cutomers throughout the day is testament to this. Not to mention the owner is an absolute joker, definitely seek him out. Wash your wrap down with a fresh homemade lemonade of carrot and ginger juice. Simples.

text.text: As much as we’d love to we can’t always afford a fancy meal out, while cheap eats often mean a compromise on quality: not here. Nope, Falafel & Shawarma is a bangin’ value for your buck and you can bet it tastes good. Mad popular with locals and boasting a beautifully simple menu, this is the perfect place for a wrap or spot of mezze, and it’s unlikely to set you back more than a fiver.
Best for… your crafty needs

tip.text:
More than a mere vessel for getting lairy in, The Stormbird is a Camberwell institution: a place to discover a whole new world of beer and, we like to think, discover a little about yourself in the process. Beer connoisseurs make the pilgrimage for the crazy big selection of international draughts with American icons, Belgian dazzlers and Danish delights all on the pumps - each with a different tap handle designed by local artists. You can cop the good stuff in pints, halves or thirds, so getting to grips with all the options is well within the realm of possibility.

Do we mind that the Stormbird's tables are slightly sticky and toilets fairly grim? No we don't. Not when it's welcomed our sorry arses in through thick and thin, and certainly not when there are £3 pints to be had. We've even been known to take a book in on a quiet evening - but please don't tell anyone.

text.text: Nowhere can be without a local craft beer boozer in this day and age. Camberwell’s Stormbird sits opposite the more typical, legendary boozer ‘Hermits Cave’ and is the complete antithesis: funny (or well clever) that they’re owned by the same people. You’ll find the likes of chocolate ice cream brown ales and local IPAs here, with your more classic lagers and such over the road. Out with a mate with differing taste? It’s cool, grab a pint at each and shout at each other over the traffic.
Best for… dopest Chinese food in town

tip.text:
For the untrained tongue, London's Chinese restaurant scene can be a nightmare to navigate so stay safe with a trip to Silk Road. Always reliable and buzzing, this unassuming Camberwell restaurant with plain interiors serves full flavoured broths, hand-pulled noodles, lamb skewers and dumplings from the Xinjiang province of China.

The only restaurant in London specialising in this cuisine, which counts the Middle East as a direct culinary influence, you can bet your bottom dollar you're in for some flavours.

text.text: Silk Road was Camberwell’s best kept secret weapon once upon a time. Not anymore though, not since Jay Rayner came through and raved about the place like Tim Westwood plugging the latest grime MC. This is the only Chinese restaurant in London to specialise in food from the Xinjiang region, an area rife with influence from the Middle East: this culminates in a wonderful and affordable menu. You will not be disappointed. It will be fucking busy, but that’s a damn good sign.
Best for… your local loveable rogue

tip.text:
This scruffy and vast wonderland of a pub is a massive middle-finger to all the fancy gastropubs you find nowadays with super try-hard 'distressed' interiors - this place ain't pristine but it's got bucketloads of character. The skylit dining room is a joy and the ample outdoor seating, both front and back of the pub, mean much in the way of summer boozing.

Catch DJs spinning here on weekends, while BBQs will be popping off every week through the sunny season. Fancy yourself a keen, quizzical mind? Test your skills at their pub quiz on a Wednesday eve at 8pm.

text.text: The distressed look and feel to this building is not a pretence: this place is the real deal and has character in fucking spades. From the old furniture to the glorious skylight over the dining room, this vast pub is exactly what you want from a local: beer garden, food, sport on the tellybox and DJs on the weekend. Honestly, it’s that swell.
Best for… Neapolitan bites

tip.text:
Every day the pizza elves at Theo’s abide by an 11-page document on what makes a Neapolitan pizza bang, resulting in a gigantic wood-fired oven doing what it does and creating delicious discs of sourdough laden with punchy flavours. But what really sets Theo's apart from other pizza purveyors is the top-shelf ingredients. Toppings are actually kept pretty simple, allowing their quality to shine through. Seasonal veggies, imported Italian meats, creamy buffalo mozzarella - it’s all packed with aroma and essence.

We just can't help but respect anywhere that makes its own (incredible) chilli sauce, shoves wine and beer into sturdy Pyrex jugs and humbly plonks everything in front of you without any particular fanfare. They know it's tasty, you know it's tasty - there's no need to tart it up with unnecessary extras.

text.text: This insanely popular pizza joint keeps the people of Camberwell coming back for more and we really can’t hate on that. Theo, owner and chef, and his team of Italian cooks are firing up some of South London’s finest Neapolitan pizzas in that oven of theirs, while the panuozzos (wood-fired sandwiches) are just absolutely the one. Wash it down with a negroni or local craft beer ‘cos why not?
Best for… cloud gazing

tip.text: This lovely Edwardian Park in Camberwell is the perfect destination for a spot of cloud-gazing and daydreaming. Equally, if you're more of an active type, Ruskin Park features tennis courts, a skatepark, a paddling pool, a vibrant flower garden and a fruit 'n' veg patch for your enjoyment. Closing time is 15 mins before sunset so be sure to have a sundial to hand.

text.text: Sometimes you just gotta take a step back from this big city life and retreat into wonders of nature. Well Ruskin Park ain’t exactly the New Forest but it’s definitely a welcome green spot round these parts - take in the vibrant flowers in the garden, have a splash in the pool, buss a trick on the ramp or have a swing of a tennis racket: whatever floats your boat pal.
Best for… street-side sippin'

tip.text:
Blink whilst walking past this itty-bitty café and you might just miss it; clutching onto the front of a fully functioning upholstery workshop, Fowlds has been breathing life into the old ‘good things, small packages’ thing since 2014. By day you’re looking at all kinds of homemade pastries, cake and coffee, whilst the evening brings with it bar snacks, craft beer and zingy cocktails.

There may be somewhat of a table shortage inside but ample seating tumbles out onto the road, providing a great spot to park up and gaze at the original 1926 upholsterers’ signage hanging out front. If you’re lucky, you might even catch craft upholstery in action. Furniture restoration and coffee? Name a more iconic duo, we’ll wait.

text.text: This immensely cosy cafe set in the front of a longstanding upholsters (called Fowlds) is out here quenching thirst left, right and centre: coffees, pale ales, prosecco and Aperol spritzes are all available. Food offerings are simple but enticing - peanut butter and banana toastie? Chocolate and Guinness cake? Hard to imagine anything more chilled than kicking back on the streetside seats and tucking into half a grapefruit (£1).
Best for... a wild night

tip.text:
Named after a Dutchman who once flew, this venue plays a special role on the queer and alternative scene, and offers some of the weirdest shit you've ever seen. It's no wonder, with a two floor venue, a 6am licence, a free exhibition space and a fit-for-purpose basement-dungeon to hire, you can pretty much organise anything you like. And people do - from fetish nights, to psychedelic trans clubs, shocking live performances, shibari workshops, intriguing exhibitions and alternative drag shows, the only limitation is your imagination.

The venue is only open for events. It's also up for hire, simply drop them an email to find out more.
